included.name: Body Mass Index and Self Esteem: A Correlational Study
included.publisher: Developing Human Potential: Issues, Perspectives and Challenges organized by D.E. Society's Fergusson College, Dept. of Psychology, Pune
included.description:
The aim of the present study was to find the relation between Body mass index and Self-esteem among young adults. The sample consisted of both girls and boys in the age group of 18-25 years (n=120). Rosenbergâs Scale was used to measure self-esteem. Body Mass Index was calculated by using a calculator provided by National Institute of Health. Pearson product moment revealed that there was significant negative correlation between Body mass index and self- esteem (r = -.629, p< 0.1). Simple regression analysis showed that Body mass index was
significant predictor of self-esteem.

included.name: Positive Emotion (happiness) enhancement on Attention
included.publisher: 2nd National Conference of Indian Association of Positive Psychology in Association with Maniben Nanavati Women's College.
included.description: Abstract: Role of Positive Emotion (Happiness) in enhancement of Attention. A two group, pre-test post-test, control group design was used in the present study to examine the effect of Positive Emotion (Happiness) in the enhancement of attention among children. A total of 410 students were selected from various schools in Pune. WISC-IV subscale of coding was used to find the children with low attention on the scale. Out of 410 children 94 found to have low attention on the scale. During this time, I could realize my passion and aptitude for research work in future.
